Malcolm Ross Kinsella Ryan writes:
 
> A couple of things about this proto:
 
> 2) I'm not sure about the "Decreasing Priority" rule. I think it needs
>    to be Plato-Pragmatised, but I don't know what would be the best way
>    to do it.

It also conflicts with the initial provision that a Proposal's
priority be an integral value.  I suggest that what you do instead is
allow the Promotor discretion to reduce the priority of any Proposal
that has been in the Queue for a whole month by one, or if it is has a
Priority of zero, remove it from the Queue entirely.  This removes any
hint of automatic actions, and gives the Promotor something more to
do. 
 
> 4) I wanted the Promotor to publish the Proposal Queue each week,
>    but to be able to do so without officially distributing the
>    proposals.  I'm not quite sure how well I've done that.
 
I suggest that it might be sufficient to amend the relevant rule to
state that a Proposal Distribution is only such if it is only
explicitly labelled as such.  (This follows the precedent set by the
way we do CFJs and Proposal submission.)

>    Thinking about it, we would probably not want the Promotor to
>    publish the entire text of every proposal in the queue, every
>    week, but e should be allowed to publish the text of yet-to-be
>    distributed proposals, (and required to when asked, by the FOIA).
 
Yeah, this would also be nice. 

> 5) The phrase "A Proposal is Emergency if..." is ugly :p. It would be 
>    much nicer to call them "Urgent Proposals". 

I agree; change the name.
 
Michael.

