On Wed, 14 Jan 1998, Steve Gardner wrote:

> >Eek.  Out of the frying pan etc.
> >
> >Sub-PROTO Effectiveness Determination (version 3)
> >
> >      The effect of a step of a procedure to change the Game State
> >      shall be determined using the best evidence available to the
> >      person primarily responsible for reporting the outcome of the
> >      procedural step.  Such a person's reasonable and good faith
> >      determination of whether the procedural step is effective is
> >      definitive, even if it is based on erroneous information.
> 
> How does this get you out of the fire? If the good faith determination
> is definitive, then Scott's worries about error have not been addressed.

The goal is to ensure that the success of a procedure is known immediately
after it is reported - that does not leave room for ignoring errors. 
Having an error take definitive effect is a feature not a bug :-)

My sub-Proto is called so for a reason:  It would have to be embedded
within some system to correct errors after the fact.  Which I assume the
Omnibus act is (I still haven't got around to read it properly...)

Such a system could be an improvement on the current system in that it
could allow errors to stand if they were insignificant, or to correct only
the immediate errors and not further consequences that cause the complete
recalculations we are so fond of (NOT).

Greetings,
Ørjan.


